      "content": "# Cognitive Testing Report: Vaccine Intent & Trust Questionnaire\n\n## Critical Findings\n\n### Comprehension Risk\n- **Item 7:** \"The CDC has my best interests in mind\" is abstract and assumes shared understanding of institutional motivation. Respondents may conflate \"interests\" with \"competence\" or \"benevolence.\"\n- **Item 10:** Double-negative construction (\"hasn't changed\" vs. \"changed too much\") requires cognitive effort; vulnerable to misinterpretation.\n\n### Double-Barrel Wording\n- **Item 3:** Conflates two distinct constructs\u2014personal protection AND family protection. Respondent who agrees they're protected but doubts family coverage is forced to choose.\n- **Item 8:** Combines two attributes (\"clearly\" and \"honestly\"). Respondents may trust honesty but doubt clarity, or vice versa.\n- **Item 13:** Asks about both \"effectiveness\" and \"safety\" in a single item; these are orthogonal constructs.\n\n### Socially-Desirable Bias Risk\n- **Item 4:** Recommendation to friends/family is subject to approval-seeking bias; respondents may inflate agreement to appear prosocial.\n- **Item 6:** Trust in institutions is high-stakes politically; respondents may bias responses toward social acceptability.\n- **Item 9:** Framing \"scientific evidence\" as objectively superior to \"anecdotes\" creates implicit moral hierarchy; may elicit acquiescence from respondents wanting to appear rational.\n\n### Acquiescence-Bias Risk\n- **Item 2:** Simple agreement statement with no negative counterpart in immediate context; yes-saying may dominate.\n- **Item 14:** Influence of social media is culturally salient and often criticized; respondents may over-report influence to align with prevailing narrative.\n\n### Scale Construction Issue\n- **Item 5:** Multiple-choice format differs from Likert scale; mixes categorical and ordinal measurement approaches, complicating analysis.\n- **Item 11:** Single-selection item lacks ordinal structure; cannot be combined with 5-point Likert items in aggregate scoring.\n\n---\n\n## Revision Recommendations\n\n### 1. **Disaggregate Double-Barrel Items**\n   - **Item 3** \u2192 Split into two items: (a) \"Vaccination is the best way to protect *me* from COVID-19\" and (b) \"Vaccination is the best way to protect *my family* from COVID-19.\"\n   - **Item 8** \u2192 Split into two items: (a) \"The CDC provides clear vaccine safety information\" and (b) \"The CDC provides honest vaccine safety information.\"\n   - **Item 13** \u2192 Split into two items: (a) \"I feel well-informed about vaccine effectiveness\" and (b) \"I feel well-informed about vaccine safety.\"\n\n### 2. **Add Negatively-Worded Items & Clarify Abstract Language**\n   - **Item 7** \u2192 Replace \"best interests in mind\" with concrete behaviors: \"The CDC bases vaccine recommendations on scientific evidence\" (and add inverse: \"The CDC prioritizes politics over safety in vaccine decisions\").\n   - **Item 10** \u2192 Simplify to: \"The CDC's vaccine guidance has been inconsistent\" (removes double-negative).\n   - Add Item 15: \"I would NOT recommend the COVID-19 vaccine to close contacts\" (inverse of Item 4 to reduce acquiescence bias).\n\n### 3. **Standardize Response Formats & Reduce Social Desirability Cues**\n   - Convert **Item 5** from checkbox to single-select categorical (align with Item 11 structure).\n   - Reframe **Item 9** neutrally: \"I rely on scientific studies when making vaccine decisions\" (remove value judgment of \"more than\" anecdotes).\n   - For **Item 14**, add temporal specificity: \"In the past 3 months, social media has influenced my views about vaccines\" (reduces telescoping and perceived norm-following).\n\n---\n\n**Items Flagged:** 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8, 9, 10, 11, 13, 14 (11 of 14 items require revision)\n"
